Anonymous Tue 27 Jun 2023 02:19:34 No.57573734 Report
Quoted By: >>57573866
>>57573293
The idea kind of makes me think of a bit of the worldbuilding from Keith Laumer's "Imperium" stories. There's a mostly benevolent-ish government on a parallel Earth that is colonizing habitable parallel Earths and trading with inhabited parallel Earths. One point that keeps coming back up is that circa 1910 in a big swath of timelines, a pair of Italian physicists came up with something really big. It is left vague as to whether it was atomic power, or a working perpetual motion machine, but they--the benevolent empire--think it was something that had the potential to be used as a planet-busting weapon, because in a great big section of parallel worlds that existed in roughly similar parallel Earths, there ain't no Earths no more, just an additional asteroid belt around the sun, in roughly the same place as the Earth's orbit in our timeline. Our world went overlooked and uncontacted for many years because it was a parallel in the same "wasteland" section of fairly similar histories, but one in which a freak accident kept the two Italian physicists from coming up with their planet-buster. Oh, and the benevolent imperialists aren't the only group out there with the technology to hop from timeline to timeline, and some of them are pretty nasty, like the bandit/pirate army that likes to pop into an uncontacted world, rob banks for gold, rob museums for artwork, and leave behind nukes as a farewell present to make investigation and pursuit more difficult.

I always kind of liked Laumer's work. It's a pity he had that massive stroke in 1971. He was only forty-six years old. He suffered prety severe brain damage and what little he wrote between then and his death in 1993 showed it.

He had some anthro-ish species as antagonists for humanity in some of his books, like the Melconians, sort of anthro wolf-ish. They were similar enough to humans, in their psychology, and in the environments they needed, that the wars were long, bloody, nightmarish slugfests.
